## Type Annotations and Declarations

In Julia, you can specify types for variables, function arguments, and return values. Type annotations help to provide clarity in your code, and in some cases, they can enable Julia‚Äôs just-in-time (JIT) compiler to generate more efficient code. While type annotations are optional, they are recommended for improving code readability and performance.

### Variable Type Annotations

You can explicitly declare the type of a variable by using a type annotation:

::: {#23487e63 .cell execution_count=28}
``` {.julia .cell-code}
x::Int = 10  # x is an integer
y::Float64 = 3.14  # y is a Float64
nothing #| hide_line
```
:::


In this example, `x` is explicitly declared as an integer (`Int`), and `y` is declared as a `Float64`. Type annotations can also be used with mutable and immutable structs.

### Function Argument Type Annotations

You can specify types for function arguments to ensure that the function only accepts values of a specific type:

::: {#4ab9f07b .cell execution_count=29}
``` {.julia .cell-code}
function add(a::Int, b::Int)
    return a + b
end

println(add(3, 4))  # Valid
